Case Study: Phishing Attack

Phishing is when someone tries to trick people online into giving their personal details like passwords or bank info. It doesn’t look like a scam at first, which is why people fall for it.

Like, suppose a student gets an email that looks like it’s from their college. It might say something like “your account will be blocked” or “verify your details.” When you see something like that, you don’t really think too much and just click the link. The link opens a page that looks almost exactly like the real website. So obviously most people won’t notice anything wrong. Then they enter their login details, thinking it’s normal, but actually those details go to the attacker.

Also sometimes just clicking the link itself can cause issues, like downloading something in the background. Most people don’t even realize that happened.

Students are targeted a lot because they are always checking emails about exams, results, fees and stuff. So if something looks urgent, they react quickly. Even working people or older people can get tricked if they’re not careful.

The consequences are not small. You can lose your account, sometimes even money. Personal data can also be misused. And one more thing is that once an account is hacked, it can be used to send the same fake messages to other people.

So basically, even if something looks real, it’s better to stop for a second and check properly before clicking anything.
